        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "CHEMISTRY "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                356,
                478,
                449,
                490
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Making chemicals with electricity "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                353,
                500,
                799,
                576
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Hydrogen can be produced in electrically heated reactors, reducing  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{CO}_{2}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " emissions "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                355,
                577,
                828,
                620
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "By Kevin M. Van Geem, Vladimir V. Galvita, Guy B. Marin "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                355,
                643,
                590,
                672
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Vast amounts of energy are needed to synthesize the hundreds of millions of tons of chemicals used in everyday life each year. To meet that demand, the chemical industry uses the energy released during fuel combustion, thereby producing a seventh of the anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases. Climate change makes it mandatory to replace fossil fuels in chemical production processes and reduce their climate impact (1-3). On page 756 of this issue, Wismann et al. (4) focus on reducing the  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{CO}_{2}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " emissions created during the production of molecular hydrogen  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(\\mathrm{H}_{2})"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", a key building block for ammonia-derived fertilizers, "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                356,
                684,
                639,
                907
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Laboratory for Chemical Technology and Center for Sustainable Chemistry, Ghent, Belgium. Email: guy.marin@ugent.be "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                356,
                924,
                629,
                948
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "through steam reforming of methane. This industrial process releases  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "9\\mathrm{kg}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{CO}_{2}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " per kg of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{H}_{2}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", a quarter of which comes from fuel combustion. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                654,
                643,
                939,
                697
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Wismann et al. show that gas-fired steam-reforming reactors (see the photo) can be substituted by electrically heated ones, thereby potentially circumventing emissions from fuel combustion (see the figure). In the electrically heated reactor, heating is based on the Joule effect (the heating that occurs when an electric current flows through a resistance). The reactor wall, which is coated with a catalytic layer, is the main electric resistance. This makes it possible to take advantage of the intimate contact between the electric heating source and the reaction site, driving the reaction close to thermal equilibrium and improving selectivity and yield. The study points the way to the possible electrification of the chemical industry. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                654,
                699,
                939,
                948
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_header",
            "content": {
                "page_header_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "INSIGHTS PERSPECTIVES "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                57,
                25,
                265,
                38
            ]
        },
        {
